      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so if i switch it to std::unique_ptr, it should handle everything automatically right? like i won't have to worry about any leftover memory sitting there? can u show me how the updated code would look using unique_ptr? i want to make sure the ownership is transferred correctly to the executeTrade function.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, `std::unique_ptr` automatically manages the deallocation, so you only own it until所有权 is explicitly transferred. Here is the corrected code where `std::make_unique` creates the smart pointer in the loop, and ownership is moved into `executeTrade` using `std::move`, ensuring the order is safely finalized:\n\n```cpp\nvoid processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> order) {\n    if (order && order->isValid()) {\n        executeTrade(std::move(order)); // Ownership transfers here\n    }\n}\n\n// In your main loop\nauto newOrder = std::make_unique<Order>(data);\nprocessOrder(std::move(newOrder)); // No need to 'delete', it handles cleanup\n```\n\nEnsure that your `executeTrade` function accepts the pointer by value (as `std::unique_ptr`) or by non-const reference to properly receive ownership; otherwise, it might leave the resource in an orphaned state.",
